---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import RelatedTools from '../components/RelatedTools.astro';
import AdSlot from '../components/AdSlot.astro';
import { recommendedLuxLevels, colorTempScale } from '../data/lightingPresets';

const path = '/office-lighting-standards';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Office Lighting Standards — Recommended Lux, CRI & Color Temperature"
  description="Learn recommended lux levels, color temperature, and CRI for offices, meeting rooms, open workspaces, and home offices based on common workplace guidelines."
  path={path}
>
  <article class="max-w-site mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-10">
    <header class="mb-10">
      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-main mb-4">Office Lighting Standards</h1>
      <p class="text-lg text-muted max-w-3xl">
        A practical overview of illuminance (lux), color temperature, and color rendering targets for
        modern workspaces — for planning and conversation, not code compliance.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="prose-content">
      <h2>Why standards matter for workspace lighting</h2>
      <p>
        Office lighting standards exist to balance visual comfort, task performance, and energy use.
        Organizations such as IES (Illuminating Engineering Society), CIBSE, and national building codes
        publish illuminance recommendations by task type. Workspace Lux summarizes the numbers most
        relevant to everyday office planning so you can discuss requirements with facilities teams,
        designers, or contractors without reading full technical manuals.
      </p>
      <p>
        Standards typically specify maintained illuminance on the work plane — usually the desk surface
        at about 30 inches (75 cm) above the floor — not raw fixture lumens. That is why calculators on
        this site convert between lux, lumens, and watts rather than relying on wattage alone.
      </p>

      <h2>Recommended lux levels by space type</h2>
      <p>
        The table below lists common target ranges used in office and workspace design. Local codes,
        client standards, or LEED/WELL requirements may differ. Always verify for your jurisdiction and
        project type.
      </p>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Space type</th>
            <th>Typical lux</th>
            <th>Notes</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {
            recommendedLuxLevels.map((row) => (
              <tr>
                <td>{row.space}</td>
                <td>{row.lux}</td>
                <td>{row.notes}</td>
              </tr>
            ))
          }
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>300 lux vs 500 lux for office work</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>300 lux</strong> suits circulation areas, some meeting rooms, and offices where tasks are
        primarily screen-based with good monitor brightness. It feels softer and uses less energy.
        <strong>500 lux</strong> is the de facto standard for general office work including reading
        printed documents, markup, and prolonged focus tasks. Many corporate fit-outs target 500 lux
        maintained on the desk. Design and inspection work often needs 750–1000 lux.
      </p>
      <p>
        Read our article <a href="/blog/300-lux-vs-500-lux-office" class="text-primary hover:underline">300 Lux vs 500 Lux for Office Work</a> for a deeper comparison.
      </p>

      <h2>Color temperature guidelines</h2>
      <p>
        Neutral white around <strong>4000K</strong> is the most common choice for corporate offices.
        Home offices and reception areas may prefer 3000K–3500K for warmth. Design studios and video
        setups often use 4000K–5000K for alertness and color discrimination. Avoid mixing very warm and
        very cool sources in the same field of view.
      </p>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Kelvin</th>
            <th>Description</th>
            <th>Typical use</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {
            colorTempScale.map((row) => (
              <tr>
                <td>{row.kelvin}</td>
                <td>{row.label}</td>
                <td>{row.feel}</td>
              </tr>
            ))
          }
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>CRI (Color Rendering Index)</h2>
      <p>
        CRI measures how accurately a light source renders colors compared to natural light. For general
        office work, <strong>CRI 80+</strong> is widely acceptable. Color-critical tasks — graphic
        design, product review, print matching — benefit from <strong>CRI 90+</strong>. When specifying
        LED products, check both CRI and R9 (red rendering), especially for skin tones and branding
        materials in client-facing spaces.
      </p>

      <h2>Uniformity and glare</h2>
      <p>
        Standards also address uniformity (how evenly light is distributed) and glare control (UGR —
        unified glare rating). A room can meet average lux on paper but still feel uncomfortable if one
        area is much brighter than another or if fixtures create direct glare on screens. Professional
        lighting design uses photometric software to model these factors; simplified calculators cannot.
      </p>

      <h2>How to use these standards in practice</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Identify the primary tasks in each zone (desk work, meeting, reception).</li>
        <li>Select a target lux range from the table above.</li>
        <li>Use the <a href="/office-lighting-calculator" class="text-primary hover:underline">Office Lighting Calculator</a> to estimate total lumens and LED wattage.</li>
        <li>Choose color temperature and CRI appropriate to the space.</li>
        <li>Validate with a qualified designer or engineer for code-compliant commercial projects.</li>
      </ol>

      <p>
        Workspace Lux tools provide simplified estimates aligned with common workplace guidance. They do
        not replace photometric studies, code review, or manufacturer-specific layout tools.
      </p>
    </section>

    <AdSlot />
    <RelatedTools currentHref={path} />
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
